msIdentifier.repository: Topkapı Palace Museum (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi) , Istanbul

summary.p: 353 fol. (according to Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives); Parchment; Shelfmark: "Saray 50385" (according to Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives); Qurʾānic text: Q 1-14:9, Q 22:44 - Q 114; 15-19 lines per page; Dimensions: 360 x 290 mm; Script style corresponds to ḥiǧāzī IV (typology of F. Déroche, 1983) see palaeography by Salome Beridze; Estimated date of production: 700-800 (?).

Images of this Qurʾān codex are found in the archives of Gotthelf Bergsträßer under shelf mark "Saray 50385" of the collection of Topkapi Sarayi where it has been kept in the early 1930s. In Bergsträßer's Geschichte des Qorans, one image of this codex is given on table IV, image 5 ("Tafel IV Abbildung 5") with the caption: "Istanbul, Saray 50385, Format 36 x 29 cm, Sure 2, 58-60" (this image from Bergsträßer's Geschichte des Qorans, table IV, corresponds to fol. 8r where it is on display as image no. 2 (fol. 8r in this database, contrary to the information in "Geschichte des Qorans" it contains Q 2, 61-63). No corresponding manuscript in the catalogue of Fehmi Ethem Karatay (Topkapı Sarayı Müzesi Kütüphanesi Türkçe Yazmalar Kataloğu, Istanbul 1962) is known neither so far.

The numbering of folios follows the figures given in the images of Bergsträßer's archives (on the photos small figures indicate folio numbers, for verso pages a small "v" is placed beside this figure). After fol. 3 two folios are not appearing in the correct order: Following the text of the Qurʾān, after fol. 3v (Q 2:20-24), fol. 5v follows (Q 2:25-27), then fol. 5r (Q 2:27-31), followed by fol. 4r (Q 2:31-35) and fol. 4v (Q 2:35-40) continuing with fol. 6r (Q 2:40-47) in the correct order.

Text ranges of the images have been idientified in collaboration with Manssur Karamzadeh and Jens Inden. The digitization of the images on films from Gotthelf Bergsträßer archives has been carried out by Tobias J. Jocham. Paleography of the manuscript has been described by Salome Beridze.

The script of this manuscript corresponds with ḥiǧāzī IV style and shows some similarities with kūfī style B.I. The vertical characters of the script slant to the right. The ʾalif is similar to ḥiǧāzī IV and also to B.Ia. The initial form of the letter group ǧīm/ḥāʾ/ḫāʾ is close to ḥiǧāzī IV, as is the medial form of the letter. In the final position the letter shows a long horizontal tail with a short final loop as in ḥiǧāzī IV. However, the final loop is abscent in some examples. The initial ʿain shows a variation from ḥiǧāzī IV, the upper hook is rounder, that resembles the kūfī C group. When the letter occurs at the end of a word, the form is closer to the B.I style. When isolated, it shows a similar form to the final ǧīm/ḥāʾ/ḫāʾ group with a horizontal tail with a short final loop. The final qāf has a long vertical tail and is close to the B.I style. The letter mīm is identical with ḥiǧāzī IV. The final or isolated nūn resembles the ḥiǧāzī IV style, as is the letter hāʾ. The lām-ʾalif ligature is close to B.Ia and ḥiǧāzī IV with the two vertical lines curving to each other. Although the script style of the manuscript shows some influence of kūfī C style and B.I, it seems to be a manuscript of ḥiǧāzī IV style according to the typology of François Déroche, 1983.

Diacritical marks are used occasionally. The letters nūn, bāʾ and fāʾ are marked quite often. The qāf is marked with a dot below the letter. The vocalisation is made by presumably red dots, as we only have access to the black and white photos from the Bergsträßer photo archive. (Salome Beridze)
